threat_severity.level_description: Severity HIGH because it was considered trojan. Other contributing factor was that it could not be run in sandboxes.

attributes.magic: ELF 32-bit LSB executable, ARM, EABI5 version 1 (SYSV), dynamically linked, interpreter /lib/ld-linux-armhf.so.3, for GNU/Linux 3.2.0, stripped

crowdsourced_yara_results.description: This signature detects the presence of a number of Windows API functionality often seen within embedded executables. When this signature alerts on an executable, it is not an indication of malicious behavior. However, if seen firing in other file types, deeper investigation may be warranted.
crowdsourced_yara_results.author: InQuest Labs

crowdsourced_ai_results.analysis: The binary is a modified OpenSSH server for ARM Linux systems, likely targeting embedded IoT devices. It includes backdoor functionality to read and process sensitive device configuration files, including passwords, from non-standard paths such as `/mnt/mtd/Config/passwdSec` and `/mnt/mtd/Config/Account1`. It also implements a custom encrypted and compressed file format, identified by magic bytes `0x22222222` and `0x11111111`, along with custom decryption routines. These modifications provide unauthorized remote access and facilitate credential theft.
